# No hardcoded secrets

Secrets, credentials, tokens, API keys, passwords, certificates, and sensitive configuration values must never be hardcoded in source code, configuration files, logs, tests, or documentation. Secure secret management mechanisms must always be used.

Apply this rule when:

- modifying source code
- handling authentication or authorization
- integrating external systems
- configuring infrastructure
- reviewing pull requests
- validating production readiness

## Agent behavior

- Use environment variables, secret stores, vaults, or CI-injected secrets per project standards; never paste real values into the repo, fixtures, or screenshots in docs.
- Replace accidental literals with placeholders in examples (`${API_KEY}` / `changeme` only where clearly non-functional); rotate any credential that may have been exposed.
- In review: flag tokens in URLs, `.env` committed to git, private keys in tree, and test doubles that mirror real production formats with real entropy.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — const apiKey = "sk-live-...";  PEM in repo; integration test hits prod with real key in source

✅ GOOD — read from process env / secret manager; tests use fakes or ephemeral test keys from CI secrets; docs show redacted samples only
```
